To design the Shape class to accommodate the new shape, you would use the Strategy pattern. The Strategy pattern allows you to define a family of algorithms, encapsulate each one as an object, and make them interchangeable. In this case, you would create an interface called ShapeStrategy that has methods to calculate the area and perimeter of the shape. The Shape class would then implement this interface. To add the new shape called Circle, you would create a new class called CircleStrategy that implements the ShapeStrategy interface. The CircleStrategy class would have its own implementation of the area and perimeter methods. The Shape class would then use the Strategy pattern to switch between different shapes. For example:

public interface ShapeStrategy {
double calculateArea();
double calculatePerimeter();
}

public class Shape {
private ShapeStrategy strategy;

public Shape(ShapeStrategy strategy) {
this.strategy = strategy;
}

public double calculateArea() {
return strategy.calculateArea();
}

public double calculatePerimeter() {
return strategy.calculatePerimeter();
}
}

public class CircleStrategy implements ShapeStrategy {
private double radius;

@Override
public double calculateArea() {
return Math.PI * radius * radius;
}

@Override
public double calculatePerimeter() {
return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
}
}

public class RectangleStrategy implements ShapeStrategy {
private double width;
private double height;

@Override
public double calculateArea() {
return width * height;
}

@Override
public double calculatePerimeter() {
return 2 * (width + height);
}
}

public class Main {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Shape circle = new Shape(new CircleStrategy(5));
System.out.println("Circle area: " + circle.calculateArea());
System.out.println("Circle perimeter: " + circle.calculatePerimeter());
}
}
This implementation allows you to add new shapes without modifying the Shape class.

