The Singleton design pattern is a creational design pattern that ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to that instance. This is useful when you want to control access to a resource or when you want to ensure that a class has only one instance. Here's an example of how to implement the Singleton design pattern in Java:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Singleton singleton1 = Singleton.getInstance();
        Singleton singleton2 = Singleton.getInstance();

        System.out.println(singleton1 == singleton2); // prints: true
    }
}
```

In this example, the `Singleton` class has a private constructor and a static method `getInstance` that returns the single instance of the class. The instance is created only when it is first requested, and subsequent requests return the same instance. This ensures that there is only one instance of the class.

The Factory design pattern is a creational design pattern that provides a way to create objects without exposing the underlying logic of object creation. This is useful when you want to decouple object creation from the rest of the application. Here's an example of how to implement the Factory design pattern in Java:

```java
public abstract class Animal {
    public abstract void sound();
}

public class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void sound() {
        System.out.println("The dog barks.");
    }
}

public class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void sound() {
        System.out.println("The cat meows.");
    }
}

public class AnimalFactory {
    public static Animal createAnimal(String type) {
        if (type.equals("dog")) {
            return new Dog();
        } else if (type.equals("cat")) {
            return new Cat();
        } else {
            throw new RuntimeException("Unsupported animal type.");
        }
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal animal = AnimalFactory.createAnimal("dog");
        animal.sound();

        animal = AnimalFactory.createAnimal("cat");
        animal.sound();
    }
}
```

In this example, the `AnimalFactory` class provides a static method `createAnimal` that returns an instance of the `Animal` class based on the type of animal requested. The `Dog` and `Cat` classes implement the `Animal` interface and provide their own implementation of the `sound` method. This decouples object creation from the rest of the application and makes it easier to add new types of animals.
